<br>
You may be correct, Shehbahn.  I don't know, I haven't looked up the numbers.<br>
<br>
But even if you are, there are so many other factors involved that it still would not convince me that, by giving up the right to legally own a gun, there would be a significant enough increase in freedom from crime to warrant it.<br>
<br>
Guns are a tool, nothing more.  Having an easily accessible tool might make an action easier, and the unavailability of a tool might make an action more difficult to the point where the perpetrator decides it's not worth the trouble.  But in either of these cases, the basic problem remains - the fact that the perpetrator, whether he performs the action or not, wants to kill someone else.  Removing a tool is a half-solution at best, that addresses none of the true underlying problems.  It is not worth it, to me, to remove the right to bear arms from law abiding, intelligent, responsible citizens in order to possibly prevent such a tool from falling into the hands of criminal, stupid, irresponsible people.  Better to deal with the people that commit crimes rather than what they commit them with.  Especially when that tool can be used to not only commit, but prevent crime.  The degree to which you agree with that last statement may vary, but nobody can rationally deny it completely. <p>Caledhon TelRana - 53 Warrior<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51701">
Vethantis Soulbonker</a> - 57 Enchanter<br><b>Revolution</b>
