<br>
In countries where guns are readily available (USA) it is logical citizens demand the right to buy and carry guns themselves since they obviously prefer to have their own gun when they encounter an armed criminal. <br>
<br>
However this is not the optimal situation, i would like to argue that both citizens and criminals would prefer an encounter where both sides are unarmed instead of an encounter where both sides are carrying guns. <br>
<br>
Unarmed encounters can only take place when the government enforces strict gun control which make guns unobtainable for the common criminal. Since there are already millions of guns spread around the USA making guns illegal wont stop criminals from obtaining guns. In Britain criminals have a hard time laying their hands on a gun because the government has always enforced a strict gun control policy (although the IRA troubles have increased the availability of guns to the criminals in the UK).<br>
<br>
In short, In countries where criminals can easily obtain a gun citizens should be allowed to arm themselves. In countries where the common criminal has a much harder time obtaining a gun strict gun control should be kept in place. An encounter with a criminal where both sides are unarmed is preferable to an encounter with a criminal where both sides carry a gun. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/ukellianne.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kellianne</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 101<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/8/02 3:50:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=187.topic&index=57>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Gun Control and Crime, the English experience</span><hr size=1> In a perfect world, there would be no crime, no criminals. In an Eutopian society everyone would live in peace and harmony. Unfortunately, we don't live there - no one does.<br>
